1rb.title: Odds ratio
1rb.clickbait: A way of expressing relative degrees of belief - if the odds are 3:2, you think the first proposition is 1.5 times as likely as the second.
1rb.text:
[summary:  Odds ratios are a way of expressing *relative* chances.  If the odds of a tree being sick to healthy are 2:3, this says that there are 2 sick trees for every 3 healthy trees.  (The *probability* of a tree being sick, in this case, is 2/5 or 40%.)

![](https://i.imgur.com/GVZnz2c.png?0)]

[summary(Technical):  [todo: math2]Odds ratios express relative chances.  E.g., if the odds for X versus Y are 2:3, this expresses that we think that proposition Y is 1.5 times as likely as proposition X.  Since this is also true if we write 6:9, odds ratios are invariant up to multiplication by a positive factor.  When an odds ratio exhausts all the possibilities (e.g., it is the odds for $Z$ vs. $\neg Z$), then we can convert its components to probabilities by normalizing them so that they sum to 1.  In the example above, the probabilities would be 0.4 : 0.6.

![](https://i.imgur.com/GVZnz2c.png?0)]

Odds ratios express relative belief: if the odds for X versus Y are 3:2, this expresses that we think that proposition X is 1.5 times as likely as proposition Y.

Like all ratios, since odds ratios express a relative quantity, multiplying all elements of the ratio by a positive scalar does not change the structure that the ratio expresses.  9:6 expresses the same ratio as 3:2.

$c > 0 \implies X:Y \cong cX : cY$  

An odds ratio can contain any number of components.  In the odds ratio 3:2:6, the first component is asserted to be half as probable as the third component.

When an odds ratio exhausts all propositions under consideration, we can convert the individual components to [ probabilities] by normalizing the components so that they sum to 1.  This in turn can be done by summing all the components of the ratio, then dividing each component by the sum:

$(x_1 : x_2 : \dots : x_N) \cong (\frac{x_1}{\sum_{i=1}^N x_i} : \frac{x_2}{\sum_{i=1}^N x_i} : \dots : \frac{x_N}{\sum_{i=1}^N x_i})$

E.g., to obtain a ratio of probabilities from the odds ratio 2:3, we write:

$2:3 \cong \frac{2}{3+2}:\frac{3}{3+2} \cong 0.4:0.6$

...and the first component then has a probability of 40%, supposing that the possibilities being considered are exhaustive.

![](https://i.imgur.com/GVZnz2c.png?0)

If we begin from an ordinary probability $\mathbb{P}(X)$, we immediately obtain the odds for $X$ vs. $\neg X$ as $\mathbb{P}(X):1-\mathbb{P}(X).$  If Andrew Jackson has a 20% probability of winning the election, his odds are $0.2 : 0.8,$ or equivalently $1:4,$ or equivalently "Andrew Jackson is one quarter as likely to win as to lose."

Odds ratios are an exceptionally convenient form to express belief updates using [1lz Bayes's Rule], since the [ prior] odds can be term-by-term multiplied by a [ likelihood ratio] to yield the [ posterior] odds.  (The posterior odds in turn can be normalized to yield posterior probabilities, but if performing repeated updates, it will be more convenient to multiply by all the likelihood ratios under consideration before normalizing at the end.)

The ratio $\mathbb{P}(X) : \mathbb{P}(\neg X)$ can potentially be viewed as a dimensionless scalar quantity $\frac{\mathbb{P}(X)}{\mathbb{P}(\neg X)}$ in the range $[0, +\infty]$.  If the odds of Andrew Jackson becoming President are 0.75 to 0.25 in favor, we can also say that Andrew Jackson is 3 times as likely to become President as not.  Or if the odds were 0.4 to 0.6, we could say that Andrew Jackson was 2/3rds as likely to become President as not.

The **log odds** are the logarithm of this dimensionless positive quantity, $\operatorname{log}(\frac{\mathbb{P}(X)}{\mathbb{P}(\neg X)}),$ e.g., $\operatorname{log}_2(1:4) = \operatorname{log}_2(0.25) = -2.$  Log odds fall in the range $[-\infty, +\infty]$ and are finite for probabilities inside the range $(0, 1).$

When using a log odds form of [1lz Bayes's Rule], the posterior log odds are equal to the prior log odds plus the log likelihood.  This means that the change in log odds can be identified with [ the strength of the evidence].  If the probability goes from 1/3 to 4/5, our odds have gone from 1:2 to 4:1 and the log odds have shifted from -1 bits to +2 bits.  So we must have seen evidence with a strength of +3 bits (a likelihood ratio of 8:1).

The convenience of this representation is what Han Solo refers to in *Star Wars* when he shouts:  "Never tell me the odds!  Only tell me the logarithm of the odds ratio!"
